# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 16s-ribosomal-rna
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for it are referred to as **16S rRNA genes** and are used in reconstructing phylogenies, due to the slow rates of evolution of this region of the gene.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Fox were two of the people who pioneered the use of 16S rRNA in phylogenetics in 1977.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Multiple sequences of the 16S rRNA gene can exist within a single bacterium.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The descriptor *16S* refers to the size of these ribosomal subunits as reflected indirectly by the speed at which they sediment when samples are centrifuged.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The 16S rRNA gene is used for phylogenetic studies as it is highly conserved between different species of bacteria and archaea.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Carl Woese pioneered this use of 16S rRNA in 1977.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] It is suggested that 16S rRNA gene can be used as a reliable molecular clock because 16S rRNA sequences from distantly related bacterial lineages are shown to have similar functionalities.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Some thermophilic archaea (e.g. order Thermoproteales) contain 16S rRNA gene introns that are located in highly conserved regions and can impact the annealing of "universal" primers.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Mitochondrial and chloroplastic rRNA are also amplified.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The most common primer pair was devised by Weisburg *et al.* (1991) and is currently referred to as 27F and 1492R; however, for some applications shorter amplicons may be necessary, for example for 454 sequencing with titanium chemistry the primer pair 27F-534R covering V1 to V3.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The two primers are almost identical, but 27F has an M instead of a C.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] AGAGTTTGATC**M**TGGCTCAG compared with 8F.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] In addition to highly conserved primer binding sites, 16S rRNA gene sequences contain hypervariable regions that can provide species-specific signature sequences useful for identification of bacteria.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] As a result, 16S rRNA gene sequencing has become prevalent in medical microbiology as a rapid and cheap alternative to phenotypic methods of bacterial identification.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Although it was originally used to identify bacteria, 16S sequencing was subsequently found to be capable of reclassifying bacteria into completely new species, or even genera.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] It has also been used to describe new species that have never been successfully cultured.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] With third-generation sequencing coming to many labs, simultaneous identification of thousands of 16S rRNA sequences is possible within hours, allowing metagenomic studies, for example of gut flora.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] In samples collected from patients with confirmed infections, 16S rRNA next-generation sequencing (NGS) demonstrated enhanced detection in 40% of cases compared to traditional culture methods; moreover, pre-sampling antibiotic consumption did not significantly affect the sensitivity of 16S NGS.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The bacterial 16S gene contains nine hypervariable regions (V1–V9), ranging from about 30 to 100 base pairs long, that are involved in the secondary structure of the small ribosomal subunit.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The degree of conservation varies widely between hypervariable regions, with more conserved regions correlating to higher-level taxonomy and less conserved regions to lower levels, such as genus and species.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] While the entire 16S sequence allows for comparison of all hypervariable regions, at approximately 1,500 base pairs long it can be prohibitively expensive for studies seeking to identify or characterize diverse bacterial communities.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] These studies commonly utilize the Illumina platform, which produces reads at rates 50-fold and 12,000-fold less expensive than 454 pyrosequencing and Sanger sequencing, respectively.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] While cheaper and allowing for deeper community coverage, Illumina sequencing only produces reads 75–250 base pairs long (up to 300 base pairs with Illumina MiSeq), and has no established protocol for reliably assembling the full gene in community samples.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Full hypervariable regions can be assembled from a single Illumina run, however, making them ideal targets for the platform.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] While 16S hypervariable regions can vary dramatically between bacteria, the 16S gene as a whole maintains greater length homogeneity than its eukaryotic counterpart (18S ribosomal RNA), which can make alignments easier.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Additionally, the 16S gene contains highly conserved sequences between hypervariable regions, enabling the design of universal primers that can reliably produce the same sections of the 16S sequence across different taxa.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Although no hypervariable region can accurately classify all bacteria from domain to species, some can reliably predict specific taxonomic levels.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Many community studies select semi-conserved hypervariable regions like the V4 for this reason, as it can provide resolution at the phylum level as accurately as the full 16S gene.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] While lesser-conserved regions struggle to classify new species when higher order taxonomy is unknown, they are often used to detect the presence of specific pathogens.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] In one study by Chakravorty et al. in 2007, the authors characterized the V1–V8 regions of a variety of pathogens in order to determine which hypervariable regions would be most useful to include for disease-specific and broad assays.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Amongst other findings, they noted that the V3 region was best at identifying the genus for all pathogens tested, and that V6 was the most accurate at differentiating species between all CDC-watched pathogens tested, including anthrax.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] While 16S hypervariable region analysis is a powerful tool for bacterial taxonomic studies, it struggles to differentiate between closely related species.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] In the families *Enterobacteriaceae*, *Clostridiaceae*, and *Peptostreptococcaceae*, species can share up to 99% sequence similarity across the full 16S gene.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] As a result, the V4 sequences can differ by only a few nucleotides, leaving reference databases unable to reliably classify these bacteria at lower taxonomic levels.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] By limiting 16S analysis to select hypervariable regions, these studies can fail to observe differences in closely related taxa and group them into single taxonomic units, therefore underestimating the total diversity of the sample.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, bacterial genomes can house multiple 16S genes, with the V1, V2, and V6 regions containing the greatest intraspecies diversity.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] While not the most precise method of classifying bacterial species, analysis of the hypervariable regions remains one of the most useful tools available to bacterial community studies.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Under the assumption that evolution is driven by vertical transmission, 16S rRNA genes have long been believed to be species-specific, and infallible as genetic markers inferring phylogenetic relationships among prokaryotes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] However, a growing number of observations suggest the occurrence of horizontal transfer of these genes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] In addition to observations of natural occurrence, transferability of these genes is supported experimentally using a specialized *Escherichia coli* genetic system.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Using a null mutant of *E. coli* as host, growth of the mutant strain was shown to be complemented by foreign 16S rRNA genes that were phylogenetically distinct from *E. coli* at the phylum level.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Such functional compatibility was also seen in *Thermus thermophilus*.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, in *T. thermophilus*, both complete and partial gene transfer was observed.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Partial transfer resulted in spontaneous generation of apparently random chimera between host and foreign bacterial genes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Thus, 16S rRNA genes may have evolved through multiple mechanisms, including vertical inheritance and horizontal gene transfer; the frequency of the latter may be much higher than previously thought.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The 16S rRNA gene is used as the standard for classification and identification of microbes, because it is present in most microbes and shows proper changes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Type strains of 16S rRNA gene sequences for most bacteria and archaea are available on public databases, such as NCBI.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] However, the quality of the sequences found on these databases is often not validated.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Therefore, secondary databases that collect only 16S rRNA sequences are widely used.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] SILVA provides comprehensive, quality checked and regularly updated datasets of aligned small (16S/18S, SSU) and large subunit (23S/28S, LSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences for all three domains of life as well as a suite of search, primer-design and alignment tools (Bacteria, Archaea and Eukarya).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] GreenGenes is a quality controlled, comprehensive 16S rRNA gene reference database and taxonomy based on a *de novo* phylogeny that provides standard operational taxonomic unit sets.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] EzBioCloud database, formerly known as EzTaxon, consists of a complete hierarchical taxonomic system containing 62,988 bacteria and archaea species/phylotypes which includes 15,290 valid published names as of September 2018.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Based on the phylogenetic relationship such as maximum-likelihood and OrthoANI, all species/subspecies are represented by at least one 16S rRNA gene sequence.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The EzBioCloud database is systematically curated and updated regularly which also includes novel candidate species.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Moreover, the website provides bioinformatics tools such as ANI calculator, ContEst16S and 16S rRNA DB for QIIME and Mothur pipeline.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] MIMt is a compact non-redundant 16S database for a rapid metagenomic samples identification.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] It is composed of 48,749 full 16S sequences belonging to 24,626 well classified bacteria and archaea species.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] All sequences were obtained from complete genomes deposited in NCBI and for each of the sequences full taxonomic hierarchy is provided.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] It contains no redundancy, so only one representative for each species was considered avoiding same sequences from different strains, isolates or pathovars resulting in a very fast tool for microorganisms identification, compatible with any classification software (QIIME, Mothur, DADA, etc).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The Ribosomal Database Project (RDP) was a curated database that offers ribosome data along with related programs and services.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The offerings included phylogenetically ordered alignments of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences, derived phylogenetic trees, rRNA secondary structure diagrams and various software packages for handling, analyzing and displaying alignments and trees.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] Due to its large size the RDP database is often used as the basis for bioinformatic tool development and creating manually curated databases.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/16s-ribosomal-rna] The RDP server was taken offline in 2023, but the software is still available for download.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Along with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA in eukaryotes, the **18S rRNA** was early identified as integral structural element of ribosomes which were first characterized by their sedimentation properties and named according to measured Svedberg units.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Given its ubiquitous presence in eukaryotic life, the evolution of the 18S rRNA was soon proposed as marker for phylogenetic studies to resolve the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] The **18S ribosomal RNA** is the structural RNA of the small subunit in the eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosome.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] The genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA is organized in a group with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA, separated and flanked by the ITS-1, ITS-2 and ETS spacer regions.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] These regions of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) are present with several hundred copies in the active genome, clustered in nucleolus organizer regions (NORs).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] In ribosome biogenesis, these genes are transcribed together by the RNA polymerase I and are processed in the nucleolus structure of the nucleus.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] The length of the 18S rRNA varies considerably in the eukaryotic phylogenetic tree, corresponding to a range of 16S-19S in Svedberg units, with the average length commonly given as around 2000 nucleotides.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] The 18S rRNA of humans has a length of 1869 nucleotides.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] The universal presence of the **18S rRNA** in eukaryotes and generally high degree of conservation in evolution allow the construction of universal primers for DNA amplification by polymerase chain reaction.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] The possible applications mirror molecular methods involving 16S rRNA of prokaryotes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Primers binding in highly conserved regions of the 18S rRNA are an important marker for biodiversity screening, allowing the amplification of unspecified or random targets from environmental samples as well as uncharacterized specimens from collections for DNA sequencing.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Subsequent sequence alignment covering the less strictly conserved segments then allows the assignment of a sample to biologic clades.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] In the case of 18S rRNA, retrieval of DNA is improved by the abundance of repeating sequences of the rDNA within eukaryotic cells, promoting the sensitivity of the analysis.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Multiple properties of the genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA have established it as an important marker gene for large-scale phylogenetic analysis and the reconstruction of the metazoan tree of life.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] The integral role in formation and function of the ribosome is a key cause for its omnipresence in eukaryotic life.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Meanwhile, the gene maintains a high degree of conservation under a persistent selective pressure in all living beings, highlighting its potential for comparison between distantly related clades.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Early studies utilizing the 18S rRNA sequence constructed the first large-scale phylogenetic trees of the metazoa.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Evidence from further studies led to the creation of several important clades, such as the Ecdysozoa and Lophotrochozoa.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] During the latter part of the 2000s, and with increased numbers of taxa included into molecular phylogenies, however, two problems became apparent.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] First, there are prevailing sequencing impediments in representatives of certain taxa, such as the mollusk classes Solenogastres and Tryblidia, selected bivalve taxa, and the enigmatic crustacean class Remipedia.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Failure to obtain 18S sequences of single taxa is considered a common phenomenon but is rarely ever reported.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Secondly, in contrast to initially high hopes, 18S cannot resolve nodes at all taxonomic levels and its efficacy varies considerably among clades.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] This has been discussed as an effect of rapid ancient radiation within short periods.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/18s-ribosomal-rna] Multigene analyses are currently thought to give more reliable results for tracing deep branching events in Metazoa but 18S still is extensively used in phylogenetic analyses.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] The **23S** rRNA is a 2,904 nucleotide long (in *E. coli*) component of the large subunit (50S) of the bacterial/archean ribosome and makes up the peptidyl transferase center (PTC).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] The 23S rRNA is divided into six secondary structural domains titled I-VI, with the corresponding 5S rRNA being considered domain VII.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] The ribosomal peptidyl transferase activity resides in domain V of this rRNA, which is also the most common binding site for antibiotics that inhibit translation, making it a target for ribosomal engineering.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] A well-known member of this antibiotic class, chloramphenicol, acts by inhibiting peptide bond formation, with recent 3D-structural studies showing two different binding sites depending on the species of ribosome.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Numerous mutations in domains of the 23S rRNA with Peptidyl transferase activity have resulted in antibiotic resistance.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] 23S rRNA genes typically have higher sequence variations, including insertions and/or deletions, compared to other rRNAs.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] The eukaryotic homolog of the 23S LSU rRNA is the 28S ribosomal RNA, with a region filled by the 5.8S ribosomal RNA.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] In general, rRNA has an essential function of peptidyl transferase.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] The stimulating core of the ribosome plays role in the peptide bond configuration.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Both peptidyl-tRNA and aminoacyl-tRNA are important for protein synthesis and transpeptidation response.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] However, 23S rRNA positions (G2252, A2451, U2506, and U2585) have a significant function for tRNA binding in the P site of the large ribosomal subunit.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] These modification nucleotides in site P can inhibit peptidyl-tRNA from binding.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] U2555 modification can also intervene with transferring peptidyl-tRNA to puromycin.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, the chemical modification of half of these positions G2251, G2253, A2439, and U2584 can not prevent the tRNA binding.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Peptidyl-tRNA of 50S subunits which binds to the P site preserve eight positions of 23S rRNA from chemical modification.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] On the other hand, mutation in 23S rRNA can also have impacts on cell growth.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Mutations A1912G, A1919G and Ψ1917C have a powerful growth phenotypes and they prevent translation while mutation A1916G has a simple growth phenotype and it leads to defect in the 50S subunits.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] The 23S ribosomal RNA is composed of six domains forming a complex network of molecular interactions.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] A central single-stranded region connects all of the domains through base-pairing of the two halves, forming Helix 26a.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Some consider Helix 26a to be Domain 0 due to its action as a central core and compact folding unit.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Comparison of 23S and 28S ribosomal RNA sequences across species demonstrate conservation of Helix 26a.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Helices continue to provide the support as the backbone of domain architecture.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] Chloroplast ribosomes from "higher" plants have an additional 4.5S rRNA created by fragmentation of 23S.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/23s-ribosomal-rna] It is located to the 3' side of 23S in the rRNA operon and corresponds to the 3' end of non-fragmented 23S rRNA.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/28s-ribosomal-rna] Combined with 5.8S rRNA to the 5' side, it is the eukaryotic nuclear homologue of the prokaryotic 23S and mitochondrial 16S ribosomal RNAs.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/28s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for 28S rRNA are referred to as 28S rDNA.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/28s-ribosomal-rna] The comparison of the sequences from these genes are sometimes used in molecular analysis to construct phylogenetic trees, for example in protists, fungi, insects, arachnids, tardigrades, and vertebrates.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/28s-ribosomal-rna] The 28S rRNA is typically 4000–5000 nt long.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/28s-ribosomal-rna] Some eukaryotes cleave 28S rRNA into two parts before assembling both into the ribosome, a phenomenon termed the "hidden break".
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The **prokaryotic small ribosomal subunit**, or **30S subunit**, is the smaller subunit of the 70S ribosome found in prokaryotes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] It is a complex of the 16S ribosomal RNA (rRNA) and 19 proteins.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] This complex is implicated in the binding of transfer RNA (tRNA) to messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The small subunit is responsible for the binding and the reading of the mRNA during translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The small subunit, both the rRNA and its proteins, complexes with the large 50S subunit to form the 70S prokaryotic ribosome in prokaryotic cells.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] This 70S ribosome is then used to translate mRNA into proteins.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The 30S subunit is an integral part of mRNA translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] It binds three prokaryotic initiation factors: IF-1, IF-2, and IF-3.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] A portion of the 30S subunit (the 16S rRNA) guides the initiating start codon (5′)-AUG-(3′) of mRNA into position by recognizing the Shine-Dalgarno sequence, a complementary binding site about 8 base pairs upstream from the start codon.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] This ensures the ribosome starts translation at the correct location.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The tightness of the bonding between the Shine-Dalgarno sequence on the mRNA and the 16S rRNA determines how efficiently translation proceeds.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Once the 16S rRNA recognizes the mRNA start codon, a special transfer RNA, f-Met-tRNA, binds and protein translation begins.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The binding site of the f-Met-tRNA on the 30S ribosomal subunit is called the "D-site" This step is required in order for protein synthesis to occur.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Then the large ribosomal subunit will bind and protein synthesis will continue.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The binding of the large subunit causes a conformational change in the 70S, which opens another site for protein translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] In order to form the translation complex with the 50S subunit, the 30S subunit must bind IF-1, IF-2, IF-3, mRNA, and f-met-tRNA.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Next, the 50S subunit binds and a guanosine triphosphate is cleaved to guanosine diphosphate and inorganic phosphate, thus dissociating the initiation factors and resulting in protein translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] This process is called "initiation" and is the slowest process of translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The small ribosomal subunit is made up of 16S rRNA and 19 full proteins.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] There is also one polypeptide chain that consists of 26 amino acids.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Conventionally, the rRNA is labeled with "H#" to indicate the helix number in high resolution images.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Proteins are labelled "S#" to indicate the different peptides involved in rRNA stabilization.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] S11 and H45 are located near the Shine-Dalgarno binding site, which is also near the IF-3 binding site.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Proteins S3, S4, S5, and S12, along with H18, are located near the channel where mRNA is present in the 30S subunit.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] The 30S subunit is the target of antibiotics such as tetracycline and gentamicin.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] These antibiotics specifically target the prokaryotic ribosomes, hence their usefulness in treating bacterial infections in eukaryotes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Tetracycline interacts with H27 in the small subunit as well as binding to the A-site in the large subunit.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Puromycin is an inhibitor of ribosomal translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Pactamycin interrupts the binding in the Shine-Dalgarno binding region in the small subunit, thus disrupting activity.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/30s] Hygromycin B also interacts with H44 and inhibits the translocation movement that is necessary during protein synthesis.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] The 40S subunit contains the decoding center which monitors the complementarity of tRNA and mRNA in protein translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] It is the largest component of several translation initiation complexes, including the 43S and 48S preinitiation complexes (PICs), being bound by several eukaryotic initiation factors, including eIF1, eIF1A, and eIF3.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] The 40S ribosomal subunit is also tightly bound by the HCV IRES to form a binary complex mediate by protein-mRNA and rRNA-mRNA interactions.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] More information can be found in the articles on the ribosome, the eukaryotic ribosome (80S), and the article on protein translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] The shape of the small subunit can be subdivided into two large segments, the head and the body.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Characteristic features of the body include the left and right feet, the shoulder and the platform.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] The head features a pointed protrusion reminiscent of a bird's beak.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] The mRNA binds in the cleft between the head and the body, and there are three binding sites for tRNA, the A-site, P-site and E-site (see article on protein translation for details).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] The core of the 40S subunit is formed by the 18S ribosomal RNA (abbreviated 18S rRNA), which is homologous to the prokaryotic 16S rRNA.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] This rRNA core is decorated with dozens of proteins.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] In the figure "Crystal Structure of the Eukaryotic 40S Ribosomal Subunit from *Tetrahymena thermophila*", the ribosomal RNA core is represented as a grey tube and expansion segments are shown in red.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Proteins which have homologs in eukaryotes, archaea and bacteria are shown as blue ribbons.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Proteins shared only between eukaryotes and archaea are shown as orange ribbons and proteins specific to eukaryotes are shown as red ribbons.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] The table "40S ribosomal proteins" shows the individual protein folds of the 40S subunit colored by conservation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Proteins which have homologs in eukaryotes, archaea and bacteria (EAB) are shown as blue ribbons.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Proteins shared only between eukaryotes and archaea (EA) are shown as orange ribbons and proteins specific to eukaryotes (E) are shown as red ribbons.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Eukaryote-specific extensions of conserved proteins, ranging from a few residues or loops to very long alpha helices and additional domains, are highlighted in red.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] For a details, refer to the article on the eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Historically, different nomenclatures have been used for ribosomal proteins.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] For instance, proteins have been numbered according to their migration properties in gel electrophoresis experiments.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Therefore, different names may refer to homologous proteins from different organism, while identical names not necessarily denote homologous proteins.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] The table "40S ribosomal proteins" crossreferences the human ribosomal protein names with yeast, bacterial and archaeal homologs.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/40s] Further information can be found in the ribosomal protein gene database (RPG).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] In molecular biology, the **5.8S ribosomal RNA** (**5.8S rRNA**) is a non-coding RNA component of the large subunit of the eukaryotic ribosome and so plays an important role in protein translation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] It is transcribed by RNA polymerase I as part of the 45S precursor that also contains 18S and 28S rRNA.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] Its function is thought to be in ribosome translocation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] It is also known to form covalent linkage to the p53 tumour suppressor protein.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] 5.8S rRNA can be used as a reference gene for miRNA detection.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S ribosomal RNA is used to better understand other rRNA processes and pathways in the cell.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is homologous to the 5' end of non-eukaryotic LSU rRNA.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] In eukaryotes, the insertion of ITS2 breaks LSU rRNA into 5.8S and 28S rRNAs.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] Some flies have their 5.8 rRNA further split into two pieces at the 3' end, forming what is called 5.8S, ITS2a, and 2S.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] L567.5 rRNA structure is approximately 150 nucleotides in size and it consists of plenty of folded strands, some of which are presumed to be single stranded.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] This ribosomal RNA, along with the 28S and 5S rRNA as well as 46 ribosomal proteins, forms the ribosomal large subunit (LSU).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is initially transcribed along with the 18S and 28S rRNA in the 45S preribosomal RNA, along with the ITS 1 and ITS 2 (Internal transcribed spacer) and a 5’ and 3’ ETS (External transcribed spacer).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The 5.8S rRNA is located between the two ITS regions, with ITS1 separating it from the 18S rRNA in the 5' direction, and ITS2 separating it from the 28S rRNA in the 3' direction.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] The ITS and ETS are cleaved away during rRNA maturation.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/5-8s-ribosomal-rna] This is accomplished through a continuous cleavage pathway performed by both endonuclease and exonuclease enzymes, cutting the spacers at specific locations.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] Despite having the same sedimentation rate, bacterial and archaeal ribosomes can be quite different.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] 50S, roughly equivalent to the 60S ribosomal subunit in eukaryotic cells, is the larger subunit of the 70S ribosome of prokaryotes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The 50S subunit is primarily composed of proteins but also contains single-stranded RNA known as ribosomal RNA (rRNA). rRNA forms secondary and tertiary structures to maintain the structure and carry out the catalytic functions of the ribosome.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] X-ray crystallography has yielded electron density maps allowing the structure of the 50S in *Haloarcula marismortui* (archaeon) to be determined to 2.4Å resolutionand of the 50S in the *Deinococcus radiodurans* (bacterium) to 3.3Å.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The large ribosomal subunit (50S) is approximately twice as massive as the small ribosomal subunit (30S).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The model of Hm 50S, determined in 2000 by Nenad Ban and colleagues in the laboratory of Thomas Steitz and the laboratory of Peter Moore, includes 2711 of the 2923 nucleotides of 23S rRNA, all 122 nucleotides of its 5S rRNA, and structure of 27 of its 31 proteins.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The secondary structure of 23S is divided into six large domains, within which domain V is most important in its peptidyl transferase activity.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] Each domain contains normal secondary structure (e.g., base triple, tetraloop, cross-strand purine stack) and is also highly symmetric in tertiary structure; proteins intervene between their helices.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] At tertiary structure level, the large subunit rRNA is a single gigantic domain while the small subunit contains three structural domains.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] This difference reflects the lesser flexibility of the large subunit required by its function.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] While its core is conserved, it accommodates expansion segments on its periphery.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] A cryoEM structure of the 50S subunit from the archaeon *Methanothermobacter thermautotrophicus* has been determined.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] It shares the 50S size/sedimentation rate and the two rRNA count, but its 23S expansion segments have more in common with eukaryotes.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] A cryoEM reconstruction of the native 50S subunit of the extremely halophilic Archaean *Halococcus morrhuae* (classified under Euryarchaeota; Stenosarchaea group) is available.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The 50S subunit contains a 108‐nucleotide insertion in its 5S rRNA, which at subnanometer resolution, is observed to emerge from a four‐way junction without affecting the parental canonical 5S rRNA structure.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] Due to the differences, archaeal 50S are less sensitive to some antibiotics that target bacterial 50S.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] 50S includes the activity that catalyzes peptide bond formation (peptidyl transfer reaction), prevents premature polypeptide hydrolysis, provides a binding site for the G-protein factors (assists initiation, elongation, and termination), and helps protein folding after synthesis.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] An induced-fit mechanism has been revealed for how 50S catalyzes the peptidyl transfer reaction and prevents peptidyl hydrolysis.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The amino group of an aminoacyl-tRNA (binds to A site) attacks the carbon of a carbonyl group of a peptidyl-tRNA (binds to P site) and finally yields a peptide extended by one amino acid esterified to the A site tRNA bound to the ribosomal A site and a deacylated tRNA in the P site.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] When the A site is unoccupied, nucleotide U2620 (E. coli U2585), A2486 (2451) and C2106 (2063) sandwich the carbonyl group in the middle, forcing it into an orientation facing the A site.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] This orientation prevents any nucleophilic attack from the A site because the optimal attacking angle is 105 degrees from the plane of the ester group.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] When a tRNA with a complete[?] CCA sequence at its acceptor stem is bound to the A site, C74 of the tRNA stacking with U2590 (2555) induces a conformational change in the ribosome, resulting in movement of U2541 (2506), U2620 (2585) through G2618 (2583).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The displacement of bases allows the ester group to adopt a new conformation accessible to nucleophilic attack from the A site.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The N3 (nitrogen) of A2486 (2451) is closest to the peptide bond being synthesized and may function as a general base to facilitate the nucleophilic attack by the amino group of the aminoacyl-tRNA (in the A site).
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The pKa of A2486 (2451) is about 5 units higher in order to hydrogen bond with the amino group thus increasing its nucleophilicity.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The elevation of pKa is achieved through a charge relay mechanism.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] This buried phosphate can stabilize the normally rare imino tautomers of both bases, resulting in an increase in the negative charge density on N3.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] After initiation, elongation, and termination, there is a fourth step of the disassembly of the post-termination complex of ribosome, mRNA, and tRNA, which is a prerequisite for the next round of protein synthesis.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The large ribosomal subunit has a role in protein folding both *in vitro* and *in vivo*.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The large ribosomal subunit provides a hydrophobic surface for the hydrophobic collapse step of protein folding.
[src:16s-ribosomal-rna/50s] The newly synthesized protein needs full access to the large subunit to fold; this process may take a period of time (5 minutes for beta-galactosidase).
